# Balasubramanian Venkatesh _v_ Zhuo Shiyun, Cheryl  

### \[2022\] SGDC 121

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">District Court Suit No 2991 of 2020</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">09 June 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">District Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Lim Mei Yee Elaine</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Ms Renuka d/o Karuppan Chettiar (Karuppan Chettiar &amp; Partners) for the plaintiff; Mr Tan Seng Chew Richard, Mr Siew Jey Ren (Tan Chin Hoe &amp; Co) for the defendant</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Balasubramanian Venkatesh — Zhou Shiyun, Cheryl</td></tr></tbody></table>

Tort – Negligence – Breach of duty

Tort – Negligence – Contributory negligence

9 June 2022 - Judgment reserved.

### District Judge Lim Mei Yee Elaine:

1       On 8 December 2018 at about 3.30pm, a collision occurred between the plaintiff’s motorcycle FBN 3606K and the defendant’s car SLX 9812X along Jurong East Avenue 1 in the direction of Jurong West. The plaintiff was injured, and his motorcycle was damaged, in the collision. The plaintiff brought this action in negligence for losses arising from the collision.

2       The trial before me was solely to determine liability. After considering the evidence and the parties’ submissions, I find the defendant 80% liable for the collision. I set out below my reasons below.

## Undisputed facts

3       Jurong East Avenue 1 (the “Road”) is a dual carriageway with two lanes in each direction. A concrete road divider separates the two carriageways. There is an opening in the road divider near Esso Jurong East petrol station to allow vehicles travelling along the Road, in the direction of Jurong West, to make a right turn into the petrol station located on the opposite side of the Road. No U-turns are permitted at the opening in the road divider.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1)

4       For convenience, I reproduce below a Google Maps photograph showing the street view of the stretch of the Road along which the collision had occurred.[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2)

![](data:image;base64,)

5       At the time of the collision, both parties’ vehicles were travelling along the Road in the direction of Jurong West. The plaintiff was travelling straight along the right lane at a slow speed.[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3) The defendant had just picked up a Grab Hitch passenger from a nearby condominium, Parc Oasis, and was sending him to town area. After exiting Parc Oasis, she made a left turn onto the left lane of the Road and travelled for a short distance before realising that she was travelling in the wrong direction. She then attempted to make a U-turn using the opening of the road divider.[^4] It is disputed whether the defendant had attempted the U-turn from the left lane or the right lane of the Road.

6       While the defendant was in the process of attempting the U-turn, the parties’ vehicles collided into each other, with the point of impact being on the right lane broadly in line with the beginning of the opening in the road divider.[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5) After the collision, the defendant’s car came to a stop ahead of the plaintiff’s motorcycle, and at an angle which was perpendicular to the direction of the traffic flow along the Road.[^6] The plaintiff, on the other hand, lost his balance on the motorcycle, fell onto the Road, and landed underneath his motorcycle.[^7] The plaintiff was eventually conveyed in the defendant’s car to Ng Teng Fong General Hospital for medical treatment.[^8]

7       The only part of the defendant’s car which was damaged in the collision was the right wing mirror, which had turned outward to the opposite side towards the bonnet of her car.[\[note: 9\]](#Ftn_9)

## The parties’ cases

8       The plaintiff’s pleaded case is that the defendant was travelling on the left lane and had suddenly cut into his lane and collided into his motorcycle. The collision was caused wholly by the defendant’s negligence in (a) failing to keep a proper lookout; (b) failing to give way to the plaintiff’s motorcycle which was going straight, before making a lane change into the plaintiff’s lane; (c) failing to stop, swerve, slow down or take any other appropriate action to avoid the collision; and (d) travelling at an excessive speed.[\[note: 10\]](#Ftn_10)

9       The following witnesses gave evidence for the plaintiff at the trial:

> (a)     the plaintiff himself;

> (b)     Mr Nithiamurugan s/o Ganapathy (“P2”), a social worker who was allegedly a passer-by and had assisted the plaintiff in the aftermath of the collision; and

> (c)     Mr Ganapathy Bharathidhasan (“P3”), a friend of the plaintiff whom he called to assist him after the collision had occurred.

10     P2 and P3 did not witness the collision, but had allegedly rendered assistance to the plaintiff in the aftermath of the collision. Their evidence was therefore confined mainly to the events which had occurred after the collision.

11     The defendant’s pleaded case is that she was on the second lane (in other words, the left lane) of the Road when the plaintiff’s motorcycle, which was travelling to her right, abruptly collided into her car, despite having seen that her car was already turning right with its signal light switched on. The defendant had checked her blind spots to ensure that there were no vehicles before she made the turn. The collision was caused wholly or substantially contributed to by the plaintiff’s negligence in (a) travelling at an excessive speed; (b) failing to ensure that it was safe for him to proceed straight when the defendant’s car was already angled to turn;[\[note: 11\]](#Ftn_11) (c) failing to give sufficient notice to the defendant of his presence; (d) failing to keep a safe distance from the defendant’s car; and (e) failing to stop, swerve or control his motorcycle so as to avoid the collision.[^12]

12     However, in her AEIC, the defendant departed from her pleaded position that she was on the left lane of the Road at the time of the collision. The defendant alleged that at the material time, she was travelling on the right lane of the Road and had attempted the U-turn from that lane.[\[note: 13\]](#Ftn_13) At trial, the defendant – who was her only witness – elaborated that she had changed lanes from the left lane to the right lane of the Road, and had been on the right lane for about four to five seconds before the collision occurred.[^14] She maintained this position in her written closing submissions.[^15]

13     I allow the defendant’s departure from her pleaded case as no irremediable prejudice was caused to the plaintiff: see _Noor Azlin bte Abdul Rahman and another v Changi General Hospital Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] 1 SLR 689</span> at \[274\]. The plaintiff had adequate opportunity to respond to the defendant’s new stance that she had made the U-turn from the right lane, as his counsel had extensively cross examined the defendant on her new stance and made arguments against it in written closing submissions.

## Issues to be determined

14     Based on the parties’ respective cases, the following are the issues to be determined:

> (a)     whether the plaintiff has proven his pleaded account of the collision;

> (b)     if the above issue is answered in the affirmative, whether the collision was caused by the defendant’s negligence; and

> (c)     whether the plaintiff was contributorily negligent and if so, how liability for the collision should be apportioned.

## Issue 1: Whether the plaintiff has proven his pleaded account of the collision

15     In my judgment, the plaintiff has proven, on the balance of probabilities, his pleaded case that the defendant was travelling on the left lane and had cut into his lane and collided into his motorcycle. This is for the following reasons.

### The plaintiff had consistently maintained that the defendant’s car came from the left lane

16     At the outset, I note that the plaintiff had consistently maintained, in his contemporaneous documents as well as throughout these proceedings, that the defendant’s car came from the left lane and collided into his motorcycle.

17     In his police report filed on 9 December 2018 (the day after the collision), the plaintiff stated that while he was travelling on the right lane, the defendant’s car, which was travelling on the left lane, made an abrupt right turn and collided into his motorcycle.[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16)

18     The sketch plan in the accident statement filed by P3 on behalf of the plaintiff on 9 December 2018 also shows that the defendant’s car was cutting from the left lane to the right lane towards the opening in the road divider and had collided into the plaintiff’s motorcycle in the process.[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17)

19     In his AEIC, the plaintiff gave evidence that while he was travelling on the right lane and was across or near Esso Jurong East petrol station, the defendant’s car came from his left side and collided into his motorcycle. He was hit from the left and then fell down to the right together with his motorcycle.[\[note: 18\]](#Ftn_18)

20     At trial, the plaintiff was firm in his evidence that the defendant’s car was not travelling ahead of him on the same lane just prior to the collision. The plaintiff testified that if the defendant’s car was travelling ahead of him on the same lane, he would have seen the car.[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19) However, he did not see the car until the collision occurred.[^20]

### The defendant’s contemporaneous documents and her pleadings state that she had attempted the U-turn from the left lane

21     Secondly, in the defendant’s own contemporaneous documents and pleadings, she took the position that she had attempted the U-turn from the left lane.

> (a)     In the “Brief Details” section of her police report filed on the day of the collision, the defendant stated in the first paragraph that “_I was on lane 2 of the road_, preparing to do a U-turn with my signal light on. After making the blindspot checks and the traffic light turn to my favour, I proceeded to on with my U-turn”[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21) (my emphasis). At trial, the defendant confirmed that she was fully aware of how lanes are marked in Singapore, and that lane 1 would refer to the right lane, lane 2 would refer to the immediate left lane, and lane 3 would refer to the lane which was left of lane 2.[^22]

> (b)     In the “Describe circumstances of the accident” section of her GIA report filed on 10 December 2018, just two days after the collision, the defendant adopted the description of the collision in her police report.[\[note: 23\]](#Ftn_23)

> (c)     In \[3\] of her Defence filed on 5 March 2021, the defendant reiterated that she was on the second lane and was already turning right, when the plaintiff’s motorcycle which was travelling to her right abruptly collided into her car.

22     It was only in her AEIC affirmed on 2 November 2021 that the defendant changed her position to allege that she had been travelling on the right lane and had attempted to make the U-turn from that lane.

23     The defendant sought to explain her change of position when she was cross examined on the statement in her police report that she was on lane 2. She alleged that she had provided many details to the police officer, including the fact that she had turned out of Parc Oasis onto the left lane of the Road, kept to the left lane and then changed lanes to the right lane in order to make a U-turn, and that the collision had occurred on the right lane. The police officer then summarised those details into the “Brief Details” section of her police report. The phrase “lane 2” was used in her police report because after she had moved off from Parc Oasis, she was initially on the left lane of the Road.[\[note: 24\]](#Ftn_24)

24     I am unable to accept the defendant’s explanation as it is unsatisfactory in two aspects:

> (a)     There is no ambiguity in the first paragraph of the “Brief Details” section of the defendant’s police report. Its plain meaning is that she was on the left lane of the Road preparing to do the U-turn, and proceeded with the U-turn after she conducted the necessary checks and the lights turned in her favour. The defendant confirmed at trial that: (i) before signing her police report, she had read that section of the report and had agreed that this was how the collision had occurred; and (ii) that section set out the information she had given to the police.[\[note: 25\]](#Ftn_25) Moreover, to-date, the defendant has not amended her police report to correct the impression given therein that she had attempted the U-turn from the left lane.

> (b)     Even in her Defence filed some two years after her police report, the defendant maintained that she was on lane 2 turning right when the collision occurred. If she had made the U-turn from the right lane, one would expect that to be reflected in her Defence.

### The defendant’s failure to see the plaintiff’s motorcycle during her alleged checks on the right lane

25     Thirdly, the defendant’s failure to see the plaintiff’s motorcycle during her alleged checks on the right lane supports his pleaded account of the collision.

26     In her police report, her Defence and her AEIC, the defendant claimed that she had checked her blind spots properly to ensure that there were no vehicles before she attempted the U-turn.[\[note: 26\]](#Ftn_26) At trial, the defendant added that she had checked not only her right blind spot, but also her rear and her right side, before attempting the U-turn.[^27]

27     I find that if the defendant had conducted these checks while she was on the right lane, she would have seen the plaintiff’s motorcycle since it is common ground that he was travelling along the right lane. However, that is not the defendant’s evidence. On the contrary, the defendant’s assertion in her police report and her AEIC that the motorcycle had suddenly appeared to her right implies that she only saw the motorcycle just prior to the collision. This undermines her stance that she had attempted the U-turn from the right lane and had conducted the necessary checks before proceeding with the U-turn.

28     In my view, the defendant’s car was likely travelling on the left lane slightly ahead of the plaintiff’s motorcycle before she filtered into the right lane in her attempt to make a U-turn. There is no indication in the evidence that the defendant was travelling at a faster speed than the plaintiff such that her car could have come from behind the plaintiff’s motorcycle on the left lane and ‘overtaken’ it before filtering into the right lane.[\[note: 28\]](#Ftn_28) The motorcycle was within the defendant’s right blind spot, and she did not check that blind spot before filtering into the right lane. Thus, she did not realise the presence of the motorcycle until just before the collision occurred.

29     As will be elaborated below, the damage to the defendant’s car, and the plaintiff’s evidence on the point of impact and the position of the car during the collision, bear out this version of events.

### The damage to the defendant’s car is consistent with the plaintiff’s evidence on the point of impact and the position of the car during the collision

30     At trial, the plaintiff gave evidence that when the defendant’s car cut into his lane from his left, it hit the left handle bar of his motorcycle, causing him to be unable to handle his motorcycle, to lose his balance and to fall to the ground along with his motorcycle. The plaintiff also gave evidence that he perceived the defendant’s car to be diagonal when it collided into his motorcycle.[\[note: 29\]](#Ftn_29) In my view, his evidence is supported by the damage caused to the defendant’s car.

31     The only part of the defendant’s car which was damaged by the collision was the right wing mirror, which had turned outward to the opposite side towards the bonnet of her car. As conceded by the defendant, the handle bar of the plaintiff’s motorcycle is the only part of the motorcycle which is at the same height as her car’s wing mirror.[\[note: 30\]](#Ftn_30) I therefore find that the left handle bar of the plaintiff’s motorcycle had side swiped the right wing mirror of the defendant’s car, while she was filtering from the left lane into the right lane in her attempt to make a U-turn. Specifically, even as the front portion of the defendant’s car was approaching the middle of the right lane, the plaintiff did not notice the car and continued to travel forward. Consequently, the left handlebar of the plaintiff’s motorcycle hit the right wing mirror of the car, causing it to turn towards the bonnet of the car.

32     As the defendant only saw the plaintiff’s motorcycle just prior to the collision, she would, in all likelihood, have braked only at around the time of the collision. It is not the defendant’s evidence that she had swerved to the left in response to the collision. In the circumstances, I find that while the defendant’s braking was taking effect, her car had likely continued moving forward into the right lane for a short distance and in the general trajectory of her intended U-turn until it came to a stop perpendicular to the direction of the traffic flow along the Road. On the other hand, as the plaintiff lost his balance after the left handlebar of his motorcycle was hit, it is likely that his motorcycle did not move forward as much as the defendant’s car. Instead, the motorcycle fell to the ground shortly after the impact. This accounts for why the damage to the defendant’s car was confined to the right wing mirror.

33     Had the defendant attempted the U-turn from the right lane as she claimed, the left handlebar of the plaintiff’s motorcycle is unlikely to have side-swiped the right wing mirror of her car.

> (a)     In the sketch plan in her accident statement, drawn by her a mere two days after the collision, the defendant depicted her car angled substantially to the right and occupying almost the entire width of the right lane at the time of the collision.[\[note: 31\]](#Ftn_31) In a similar vein, the defendant asserted in her AEIC that her car was already “substantially into the turn”, such that “there was no way that the plaintiff could have missed the U-turning of \[her\] vehicle”, when the plaintiff’s motorcycle suddenly appeared to her right and drove straight into the right side of her car.[^32]

> (b)     If the aforesaid positions in the defendant’s sketch plan and AEIC were true, the point of impact would likely have been between the wheel of the plaintiff’s motorcycle and the right side body of the defendant’s car, and the collision would likely have caused damage to the right side body of the car. However, that is not the point of impact, or the damage to the car, in the present case.

> (c)     Unsurprisingly, at trial, the defendant retreated from the position in her sketch plan and AEIC. She claimed that her car was only at a slight angle towards the right (almost parallel to the plaintiff’s motorcycle) at the point of impact, thus accounting for why the impact was only between her car’s right wing mirror and the motorcycle’s left handlebar.[\[note: 33\]](#Ftn_33) Her retreat underscores the implausibility of her claim that she had attempted the U-turn from the right lane.

### The resting position of the defendant’s car coheres with the plaintiff’s pleaded account of the collision

34     Finally, the evidence of the plaintiff and P2 on the resting position of the defendant’s car also coheres with the plaintiff’s pleaded account of the collision.

35     The plaintiff testified at trial that when he was lying beneath his motorcycle on the ground near the road divider, he saw the defendant’s car block the right lane and part of the left lane.[\[note: 34\]](#Ftn_34)

36     P2 gave evidence that when he arrived at the accident scene, he noticed that the defendant’s car was perpendicular to the direction of the traffic flow along the Road and was blocking the right lane and about half of the left lane.[\[note: 35\]](#Ftn_35) In this regard, P2 testified that in light of the width of the lanes on the Road and the length of the defendant’s car, which was a Honda Shuttle, there was no way that the car would not have obstructed the left lane as well. However, as there was a carpark entrance to the left of the left lane (as seen in the Google Maps photograph at \[4\] above), cars on the left lane could use that entrance to manoeuvre around the defendant’s car, which was why traffic on that lane was still moving.[^36]

37     I accept their evidence that the defendant’s car, in its resting position, was perpendicular to the traffic flow along the Road and had partly obstructed the left lane, though I do not think the obstruction was to the extent described by P2. Earlier, I had found that while the defendant’s braking was taking effect, her car had continued moving forward into the right lane and in the general trajectory of her intended U-turn until it came to a stop (see \[32\] above). Flowing from that finding, and in light of the length of the defendant’s car, I hold that her car had likely stopped at an angle that was perpendicular to the traffic flow, with the rear of the car on the left lane and partially in the bottom righthand side of the yellow box in front of the carpark entrance. This explains why the plaintiff and P2 observed that the defendant’s car had partly obstructed the left lane, and why P2 further observed that cars on the left lane were able to use the carpark entrance to manoeuvre around the defendant’s car.

38     The defendant submitted that the plaintiff’s evidence as set out at \[35\] above was not credible. In particular, the plaintiff could not have seen the obstruction posed by the defendant’s car on the left lane, and yet claim that he was unable to confirm the passage of other vehicles in that lane.[\[note: 37\]](#Ftn_37) I respectfully disagree. The plaintiff had explained that he could not recall whether traffic continued to pass on the left lane, because he was in pain.[^38] I accept his explanation. When the plaintiff was lying on the Road underneath his motorcycle after the collision, it is natural for his attention to be drawn to the vehicle that had collided into him. That being said, it is undisputed that the plaintiff was in great pain at the time.[^39] It is entirely conceivable that due to the pain, he did not pay attention to, and could not remember, the state of the traffic flow on the left lane.

### The credibility and independence of the plaintiff and his witnesses

39     A substantial portion of the defendant’s written closing submissions was devoted towards showing that the plaintiff, P1 and P2 are not credible, and that P1 and P2 are not independent witnesses. The defendant relied primarily on the following matters in support of this submission:

> (a)     alleged inconsistencies between the evidence of the plaintiff, P2 and/or P3 on the events that occurred after the collision;

> (b)     the plaintiff’s communications with P2, and the fact that the plaintiff, P1 and P2 stated in their police reports that they became involved in the accident from 1530 hours; and

> (c)     the plaintiff’s failure to mention during his interview with the traffic police in December 2020 that he had an independent witness, i.e., P2.

40     In my judgment, these matters do not affect my finding that the plaintiff has proven his pleaded account of the collision.

#### Alleged inconsistencies between the evidence of the plaintiff, P2 and/or P3 on the events that occurred after the collision

41     The defendant highlighted that there were inconsistencies between the evidence of the plaintiff, P2 and/or P3 on the following events:

> (a)     who extricated the plaintiff from underneath his motorcycle;[\[note: 40\]](#Ftn_40)

> (b)     where the plaintiff was moved to after his motorcycle was lifted off him;[\[note: 41\]](#Ftn_41)

> (c)     the timing of P2’s alleged arrival at the accident scene;[\[note: 42\]](#Ftn_42)

> (d)     whether P2 was already at Esso Jurong East petrol station when P3 first arrived there;[\[note: 43\]](#Ftn_43)

> (e)     whether P2 had provided his particulars to the plaintiff at the petrol station;[\[note: 44\]](#Ftn_44)

> (f)     who was responsible for bringing the plaintiff’s motorcycle to the petrol station;[\[note: 45\]](#Ftn_45) and

> (g)     to where, and when, the defendant’s car was shifted after the collision.[\[note: 46\]](#Ftn_46)

42     The defendant contended that the inconsistencies showed that the plaintiff, P2 and P3 were economical with the truth.[\[note: 47\]](#Ftn_47)

43     I find that there were inconsistencies between the evidence of the plaintiff, P2 and/or P3 on the events set out in \[41(a),(b),(d)-(f)\] above. My reasons for this view are set out in Annex 1 of this judgment.

44     However, these inconsistencies do not undermine the credibility of the plaintiff’s pleaded account of the collision. They do not pertain to the circumstances leading up to the collision, but only to the events that occurred _after_ the collision. I also did not take into account any of the evidence that was affected by these inconsistencies in reaching my conclusion that the plaintiff has proven his pleaded account of the collision.

45     In any event, I do not agree that these inconsistencies show that the plaintiff, P2 and P3 were economical with the truth. These inconsistencies are likely attributable to imperfect recall on the part of the plaintiff, P2 and/or P3, given that:

> (a)     the collision had occurred a few years ago;

> (b)     the plaintiff was in great pain after the collision, and this may have affected his ability to recall with precision the events which happened in the aftermath of the collision;

> (c)     when P2 was cross examined on the events after the collision, he stated, at one point, that he honestly could not remember the exact details because it was raining at the time, visibility was poor and the collision had occurred three years ago;[\[note: 48\]](#Ftn_48)

> (d)     at trial, P3 admitted that he could not remember numerous matters such as:

>> (i)       whether he saw anyone else apart from P2 and a Tamil man (whom he believed was an employee at the petrol station) at the petrol station;[\[note: 49\]](#Ftn_49)

>> (ii)       whether he saw anyone besides the defendant talking to the plaintiff when he arrived at the petrol station;[\[note: 50\]](#Ftn_50)

>> (iii)       whether anyone besides himself and Asuk (a mutual friend of his and the plaintiff) had helped the plaintiff into the defendant’s car;[\[note: 51\]](#Ftn_51)

>> (iv)       whether, at Ng Teng Feng General Hospital, the plaintiff was brought into the triage room after waiting for a while;[\[note: 52\]](#Ftn_52) and

>> (v)       whether anyone had approached the plaintiff at the petrol station to inform him that they could be a witness;[\[note: 53\]](#Ftn_53)

> (e)     in my view, P3’s aforesaid admissions illustrate a genuine inability on his part to recall some of the events that occurred after the collision. If P3 were truly economical with the truth, it is more likely than not that he would have testified, among other things, that he saw P2 tell the plaintiff at the petrol station that he could be a witness. Instead, P3 testified that he could not remember clearly whether anyone had approached the plaintiff to inform him that they could be a witness, because he was preoccupied with attending to and assisting the plaintiff who was in severe pain.[\[note: 54\]](#Ftn_54)

46     Furthermore, I do not accept the defendant’s submission that these inconsistencies show that P2 was not present in the aftermath of the collision to assist the plaintiff. In P2’s police report filed a month after the collision, he stated, among other things, that he was driving along the Road in the direction of Jurong West when he came across the accident scene, that he stopped and assisted the parties involved in the collision, that the plaintiff was injured and the defendant assisted to convey the plaintiff to the hospital for medical treatment, and that he had exchanged contact numbers with the plaintiff so that he could assist him.[\[note: 55\]](#Ftn_55) The defendant would have had sight of P2’s police report before she signed her AEIC and in any event, before she gave evidence at the trial. However, she did not give evidence in her AEIC or at trial that P2 was not present in the aftermath of the collision to assist the plaintiff and had not exchanged contact numbers with the plaintiff.

#### The plaintiff’s communications with P2, and the statement in theirs and P3’s police reports that they became involved in the accident from 1530 hours

47     It is not disputed that the plaintiff was physically present when P2 made his police report and when P2 affirmed his AEIC at the office of the plaintiff’s solicitors. At trial, the plaintiff alleged that it was necessary for him to meet P2 when P2 had to affirm his AEIC, because P2 did not know the way to the solicitors’ office whereas the plaintiff did.[\[note: 56\]](#Ftn_56)

48     The defendant submitted that this allegation was inherently incredible, and was in any event demolished by P2’s testimony that he could use GPS to find his way to the solicitors’ office.[\[note: 57\]](#Ftn_57) The defendant further submitted that the meetings between the plaintiff and P2 were an attempt by the plaintiff to influence the evidence of P2, since there was no necessity for the plaintiff to be physically present when P2 made his police report and when P2 affirmed his AEIC. Furthermore, evidence of coordination could be seen from the fact that the plaintiff, P2 and P3 stated in their police reports that they became involved in the accident from 1530 hrs, even though that was physically impossible.[^58]

49     The defendant also contended that P2’s denial that he had any telephone conversations with the plaintiff was a lie. The plaintiff himself had testified to having numerous telephone conversations with P2. Moreover, it would be astonishing if the plaintiff had not contacted P2 through his telephone, as there was no other way the second and subsequent meetings between them could have come about.[\[note: 59\]](#Ftn_59)

50     I agree with the defendant that there was strictly no necessity for the plaintiff to accompany P2 when P2 made his police report and when P2 subsequently affirmed his AEIC. The plaintiff’s explanation for meeting P2, when the latter was affirming his AEIC, is therefore odd. However, this factor alone is insufficient to support a finding that the plaintiff had in fact influenced P2’s evidence in his police report and his AEIC. Moreover, the fact that the plaintiff, P2 and P3 stated in their police reports that they became involved in the accident from 1530 hrs does not point inevitably to coordination of their evidence. I will not speculate on what was the actual reason for this similarity because the plaintiff and his witnesses were not cross examined and hence, did not have the opportunity to address the Court, on this matter. But suffice to say, there are other plausible reasons (apart from deliberate coordination of their evidence) to account for this similarity, such as an inability to recall exactly what time they became involved in the accident, as a result of which they defaulted to the rough timing of “about 1530 hrs” which was the estimated time of the collision.

51     I am also not satisfied that P2 had deliberately lied about not having telephone conversations with the plaintiff. It is more likely that either he or the plaintiff recalled incorrectly whether they had telephone conversations with each other. Telephone conversations (i.e., phone calls) are not the only way the second and subsequent meetings between the plaintiff and P2 could have come about. There are other possibilities, such as text messages or emails from the plaintiff and/or his solicitors.

52     In any event, I did not rely on any evidence from P3 in reaching my conclusion that the plaintiff has proven his pleaded account of the collision, and the only piece of evidence from P2 which I relied on was his evidence regarding the resting position of the defendant’s car. Even if I were to disregard that piece of evidence, I would have reached the same conclusion that the plaintiff has proven his pleaded account of the collision. In the premises, I fail to see how the defendant’s allegation of coordination of evidence between the plaintiff, P1 and P2 undermines the plaintiff’s pleaded account of the collision.

#### The plaintiff’s failure to mention P2 during his interview with the traffic police

53     It is not disputed that the plaintiff did not mention, during his interview with the traffic police in December 2020, that he had an independent witness, P2. The plaintiff’s explanation for this omission was that he was not asked about the independent witness, and could only have told the traffic police if they had asked.

54     I do not find the plaintiff’s explanation to be satisfactory. There was nothing to stop the plaintiff from mentioning P2 to the police even if they did not ask him about it. That being said, his failure to mention P2 was likely an innocent omission on his part, given that P2’s evidence (in particular, on the resting position of the defendant’s car) would have supported his account of the collision.

## Issue 2: Whether the collision was caused by the defendant’s negligence

55     In light of my findings on the circumstances leading up to the collision (in particular, \[28\] above), I hold that the defendant was negligent in:

> (a)     failing to keep a proper lookout for vehicles on the right lane, before she filtered from the left lane to the right lane in her attempt to make a U-turn; and

> (b)     failing to give way to the plaintiff’s motorcycle which was going straight on the right lane and had the right of way.

56     If the defendant had kept a proper lookout and given way to the plaintiff’s motorcycle, the collision would likely have been avoided.

57     On the other hand, I do not think the defendant can be held to be negligent for travelling at an excessive speed. As mentioned earlier, there is no indication in the evidence that she was travelling at a faster speed than the plaintiff, and it is undisputed that the plaintiff was travelling at a slow speed.

## Issue 3: Whether the plaintiff was contributorily negligent, and the apportionment of liability between the parties

58     I have found that the plaintiff did not notice, prior to the collision, that the defendant’s car travelling slightly ahead of him on the left lane was filtering into his lane (see \[28\] above). Since it is not the plaintiff’s pleaded case that the defendant had failed to signal her intention to change lanes, and the only evidence on signalling is the defendant’s unchallenged evidence that she had signalled,[\[note: 60\]](#Ftn_60) I find that the plaintiff had failed to notice the defendant’s car even though the defendant had signalled.

59     Consequently, I find that the plaintiff was contributorily negligent in failing to keep a proper lookout and failing to take any evasive action (such as applying his brakes) to avoid the collision.

60     The question is how liability for the collision should be apportioned between the parties. In my judgment, the present case is analogous to scenario 20 of _Motor Accident Guide: A Guide on the Assessment of Liability in Motor Accident Cases_ (Mighty Minds Publishing Pte Ltd, 2nd Ed, 2016) (“MAG”). In that scenario, vehicle X is changing lanes while vehicle Y is moving straight ahead in the same direction within its own lane. The suggested apportionment of liability, where driver X has signalled his intention to change lanes, is:

> (a)     80% on driver X for failing to keep a proper lookout and failing to change lanes only when there is no approaching vehicle and it is safe to do so; and

> (b)     20% on driver Y for failing to keep a lookout for vehicles effecting a lane change and failing to take evasive action to avoid a collision.

61     The 80:20 apportionment for scenario 20 of MAG is simply a guideline, and the Court may depart from it where the circumstances of the case so warrant. However, I find that nothing in the present case warrants a departure from the suggested apportionment.

## Conclusion

62     In the premises, I apportion liability for the collision at 20% on the part of the plaintiff and 80% on the part of the defendant. There shall be interlocutory judgment for the plaintiff to the extent of 80% of the damages to be assessed. Costs and interest are reserved and to be dealt with at the conclusion of the assessment of damages.

A.2    There were no inconsistencies between the evidence of the plaintiff, P2 and/or P3 on the following events:

<table align="left" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="Judg-2-tblr" frame="all" pgwide="0"><colgroup><col width="27.62%"><col width="72.38%"></colgroup><tbody><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Event</b></p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Evidence of the plaintiff, P2 and/or P3</b></p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">The timing of P2’s alleged arrival at the accident scene</p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">In his AEIC and at trial, P2 gave evidence that he was the one who lifted the motorcycle off the plaintiff and brought him to the petrol station, after which he returned to his car (which he had stopped on the right lane of the Road) and sent his Grab Hitch passenger to Jurong West before returning to the petrol station about 10 to 15 minutes later.<span class="FootnoteRef"><a href="#Ftn_82" id="Ftn_82_1"><sup>[note: 82]</sup></a></span></p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">As for the plaintiff, he testified at trial that the accident happened and P2 assisted him. He thinks that P2 had a passenger in his car, dropped his passenger at Jurong West and then returned about 10 minutes later. P2 was one of the persons who assisted him. P2 was present when the motorcycle was lifted off the plaintiff.<span class="FootnoteRef"><a href="#Ftn_83" id="Ftn_83_1"><sup>[note: 83]</sup></a></span></p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">The plaintiff’s aforesaid testimony must be read in its proper context. In cross-examination, the plaintiff had agreed that it was possibly less than two minutes after the collision that the motorcycle was lifted off him.<span class="FootnoteRef"><a href="#Ftn_84" id="Ftn_84_1"><sup>[note: 84]</sup></a></span> Thus, the correct understanding of the plaintiff’s testimony is that shortly after the accident, P2 had assisted him (and was present when the motorcycle was lifted off him), and had thereafter proceeded to send his passenger to Jurong West before returning to the petrol station about 10 minutes later. This reconciles the plaintiff’s evidence that on the one hand, the accident happened, P2 assisted him and P2 was present when the motorcycle was lifted off him, and on the other hand, P2 returned about 10 minutes later after dropping off his passenger.</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">In the premises, I find that the evidence of the plaintiff and P2, regarding the timing of P2’s arrival at the accident scene, are consistent.</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="r" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">To where, and when, the defendant’s car was shifted after the collision</p></td><td align="left" class="" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">The plaintiff stated in his AEIC that he, his motorcycle and the defendant’s car were moved “to the side of the road” and he then called P3.<span class="FootnoteRef"><a href="#Ftn_85" id="Ftn_85_1"><sup>[note: 85]</sup></a></span> It is not disputed that after the accident, the first place the parties’ vehicles were moved to was the petrol station, and that the plaintiff had called P3 at the petrol station. Thus, the phrase “side of the road” used in the plaintiff’s AEIC must be understood to mean the petrol station.</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">P2 stated in his AEIC that the defendant’s car was on the road even after the plaintiff’s motorcycle had been shifted to the petrol station.<span class="FootnoteRef"><a href="#Ftn_86" id="Ftn_86_1"><sup>[note: 86]</sup></a></span> At trial, he testified that after sending his passenger to Jurong West and returning to the petrol station, he witnessed the defendant assisting to convey the plaintiff to the hospital for medical attention, which implies that the defendant’s car was already at the petrol station by that time.<span class="FootnoteRef"><a href="#Ftn_87" id="Ftn_87_1"><sup>[note: 87]</sup></a></span> His evidence is not inconsistent with the plaintiff’s evidence, as the plaintiff did not allege in his AEIC or at trial that the defendant’s car was shifted to the petrol station at the same time as his motorcycle.</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">P3 testified at trial that the defendant’s car was already in the petrol station by the time he arrived.<span class="FootnoteRef"><a href="#Ftn_88" id="Ftn_88_1"><sup>[note: 88]</sup></a></span> Contrary to the defendant’s submission,<span class="FootnoteRef"><a href="#Ftn_89" id="Ftn_89_1"><sup>[note: 89]</sup></a></span> P3 had never indicated that the defendant brought her vehicle over to the petrol station only when the plaintiff had agreed to be sent to the hospital in her car. P3 simply said “she brought her vehicle” in NE 52/31, without saying whether the defendant had driven her car from the Road to the petrol station, or from where she had parked it in the petrol station to where the plaintiff was resting in the petrol station.</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">In the premises, I find that there are no inconsistencies between the evidence of the plaintiff, P2 and P3 regarding where, and when, the defendant’s car was shifted after the collision.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>
